	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
	
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			I disagree with some of the comments above. The bolt is &quot;unguided&quot; ? Looks very guided to me (or maybe Verant made a patch about it since). You can almost turn your back at your target, and the bolt will turn around you and hit it. Sometimes, I use the /assist command to target, and I don't know exactly where my target is; the bolt shows me the way ! :)<BR>
The real drawbacks are:<BR>
- Mana cost too high for frequent use by lev 8 and 9 wizards (and the 3rd rank spells being very expensive I would advise to buy Shock of Ice first),<BR>
- If you target a creature UPHILL the bolt will often smash in the ground at its feet,<BR>
- Longer time (versus Shock of Ice) between beginning of casting and damage dealing. But I never noticed anything such as my ozn auto-attack interrupting the spell, as mentioned above. I'm pretty sure that spell casting has priority on auto-attack.<BR>
The real advantages are:<BR>
- Longer range than shock spells (so it's good to begin with that one and start casting the shock while the creature runs at you),<BR>
- BEAUTY of the spell (which is an important factor, if only to show-off).
			</font>
	
		</td>
	</tr>
	
